    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the advice. i'm a bit worried that just talking to them individually won't work though. they both seem to enjoy the little power plays and it feels very intentional. it's like they are both trying to scavenge for any small mistake the other makes just to use it against them in public. how do i deal with that specific kind of behavior?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It sounds like you're dealing with a more manipulative dynamic, where they're trying to gain an upper hand by exploiting each other's mistakes. That's a tough one to crack, but I'd say it's time to take a more strategic approach. You can't let them turn the meetings into a game of \"gotcha\" – that's just going to create more tension and make the situation worse. \n\nOne thing you can try is to establish clear expectations for how you want the meetings to be conducted. Make it clear that you value open and respectful communication, and that any behavior that undermines that will not be tolerated. You can say something like, \"I want to make sure we're all on the same page and working together effectively. Let's make a conscious effort to communicate respectfully and avoid criticizing each other in public.\"\n\nAnother approach is to try to shift the focus away from individual contributions and towards the team's goals. You can say, \"Let's focus on the bigger picture and how our individual ideas can contribute to the team's success. We don't need to tear each other down to get there.\" \n\nIt's also worth considering whether there's a power imbalance at play – are they both trying to assert dominance over each other",
      "source": "target",
